Scottish private schools have traditionally had good learning outcomes, and this success has continued in 2018 as a result of good test results. Success has been amplified by individual and community success in sport, art, music and other community projects.
These schools with more than 30,000 pupils across Scotland, represented by the Scottish Council of Private Schools (SCIS), aim to provide a high level of service to their pupils and their parents.
Private schools strive to prepare their students for their chosen careers, for graduate and higher education, and for world citizenship.
As an educational sector operator that can design and implement tailored study content, we have noticed the status of languages as a popular and desirable subject in educational institutions.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to a person in a language he understands, the message will go to his head.
If you speak to a person in his or her own language, the message will go to his or her heart.”
This is a strong reminder that we cannot rely solely on the English language if we want to build relationships of trust with people from other countries.
From this year’s most recent test results, we can see that languages are at the top of the list in terms of the pass rate among private schools.
68% of students who studied foreign languages achieved the highest grade A.
The data were collected from 74 schools belonging to SCIS, and it was found that 72% of the pupils who received the highest grade A studied Mandarin Chinese, 72% studied German, 69% studied French and 63% studied Spanish.
This shows that private schools in Scotland support the study of foreign languages as an essential skill that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are currently optional subjects, but they are valued in the same way as natural science subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics), both in the private school curriculum and elsewhere.
According to a survey conducted by the UK Employment Office in 2014, 17 per cent of situations where an employer had difficulty finding a suitable employee were explained by lack of language skills.
The development of language skills is therefore all the more necessary for the future career development of young people.
The more language skills are required for potential jobs, the more relevant these skills become in a global world.
If a person has studied a second language, he or she will have an advantage over this lifelong skill in the future, regardless of the career he or she has chosen.
The ability to communicate directly with a foreigner automatically puts the language-speaking person ahead of the competition.
According to a survey conducted by YouGov in 2013, 75 percent of over 4,000 UK adults are unable to communicate in a foreign language, and French was the only language that could be spoken by a two-digit number of 15 percent.
This is why investing in language teaching is important for today’s children.
In particular, knowledge of the languages of developing countries gives children a better chance of finding meaningful careers.
Within Scotland, schools differ in what languages they teach.
Several schools focus on traditional languages, while some specifically teach languages that are supposed to be important to British people in 2020, such as Mandarin Chinese and Japanese.
Regardless of your child’s interests, private schools always have a number of language options taught by specialized teachers.
Private schools in Scotland are dedicated to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future may bring.
In this time, it cannot be denied that in the international business environment,languages will continue to be of great importance for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should indeed be seen as "international communication skills".
Private schools will continue to offer this freedom of choice, diversity and high standard to young people in Scotland.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is the director of the SCIS of the Scottish Council of Private Schools.
