Harvard students complete an adequate rest instruction course
This year, all undergraduate students at Harvard University take part in a course designed to increase student rest, a countermeasure to the university’s thriving macho culture, where students weigh long nights with the power of caffeine.
According to the researcher, students at the best university in the world are often quite ignorant about the basics of their own well-being.
The course was designed by Charles Czeisler, a professor of medicine at Harvard University who works on sleep research at Brigham and Women’s Hospital, and believes the course will be the first of its kind in the United States.
Czeisler got the idea for the course after he lectured on the effect of sleep deprivation on learning.
“After the lecture, a young woman came to me and said, ‘Why do I hear about it now, in my last year of school?’
No one had ever told him about the need for sleep, which I thought was surprising," he said in an interview with the Telegraph.
The course, held for the first time this year, will guide students on how proper sleep habits support academic and athletic performance and improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of medicine at Harvard University and deputy director of health services at the university, said the university had ended up hosting the course after hearing how students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the study week.
The one-hour course includes a set of interactive tasks.
One section presents a picture of a dormitory room where students can click on coffee cups, curtains, sports equipment and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of sleep deprivation on sports performance and the importance of regular evening activities.
In the second section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
With interactive icons, the campus map encourages participants to reflect on their daily routines.
“We know that this has no direct impact on student behavior.
We believe, however, that they have a right to know about these things just as much as they have a right to know about the health effects of smoking,” Professor Czeisler adds.
All-night study marathons are still a matter of pride, according to Professor Czeisler, and modern technology and the ever-increasing pressures on students made sleep deprivation a growing problem.
"Getting adequate and quality sleep should be a student's 'secret weapon' against stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, and even against weight gain because sleep deprivation causes a state of hunger in the brain, which is why a person is constantly hungry," the professor notes.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student of chemical and physical psychology in California, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of the courses he taught in his first year at Harvard last year.
He says that the course opened his eyes and gave an impetus to arranging a comprehensive course for all students on the campus.
He hopes that all postgraduate students will be able to complete a similar course of study before moving to a competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students also set an alarm clock to remind them of bedtime in addition to waking up in the morning, and urges them to bear in mind the adverse effects of electronic display devices and LED lighting on circadian rhythms, which can make it difficult to fall asleep.
