Situation of Red Tide algal blooms: concentrations drop in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
According to the latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission, there is a general decline in algae numbers in the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, more dispersed algae areas are reported in the Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, indicating a possible decrease in concentrations.
Red tide algae blooms along the coast for a distance of about 130 miles from Pinellas to the southern districts of Lee.
Ferries can be observed ten miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but there are fewer of them than last week.
Red tide blooms have also been observed in Pasco County.
Moderate concentrations were reported from the coast of Pinellas County last week, ranging from low to high on the coasts of Hillsborough County, from background to high in Manatee and Sarasota County, from background to moderate in Charlotte County, and from background to high in Lee District and Collier County.
Respiratory symptoms are still reported in the Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier regions.
Over the past week, there have been no reports of respiratory symptoms in northwest Florida.
